The book being too boring it doesnโt interest the target audience
Not explaining programming concepts clearly enough for an audience of children to understand

Our team proposes to create a vibrant graphic novel in which we use an engaging plot as a vehicle to communicate basic principles of programming (without actual code) in a fun and modern way to grade school aged children. This project is good for the team because it enables us to cross-functionally employ both our creative and technical skills towards the development of a unique product that we can all have pride in having helped create.

However, the education that children receive in K-12 regarding this subject is sparse at best.  If a student is lucky, their high school might offer an AP Computer Science class, but even that program is not reaching many people, as is evidenced by the fact that the Computer Science AB exam was recently removed by the AP Board through lack of interest (only Computer Science A remains).  How is a child to know what they want to do with their life if they are not even exposed to all the choices at a preliminary level before they enter college?  TEMA believes that young children need greater exposure to basic programming concepts.  By presenting this information through the medium of a graphic novel, we hope to simultaneously engage and educate middle school age children.
As computer science students progressing towards graduation, we possess an understanding of just how much demand there is for computer science majors in the business world.

The project must meet both of these criteria in order to be considered a success.  Neither a book that is entertaining with no educational value nor an educational book that no child wishes to read will fulfill the initial premise of the project.
